Thatâ€™s right! The spread of blood in an epidural hematoma is limited by sutures where the periosteum is continuous between the internal and external surfaces of the cranial bones. This explains the typical lens shape of this type of intracranial bleed.

CSF is black in CT, as seen here in the lateral ventricles (A). Acute blood (a bleed) is white in CT (B). 
In an extradural hematoma, arterial blood  accumulates between the periosteal layer of the dura and the cranial bone. The high pressure of the arterial blood tears the periosteum away from the bone and creates an extradural space. Extradural hematomas often involve an initial â€œlucid periodâ€ during which the patient may deny serious injury, and may not seek medical attention. This can then be followed by a rapid decline.
Extradural hematomas appear lens-shaped, in contrast to the crescent shape of the subdural hematoma and the classic â€œgyral enhancementâ€ of the subarachnoid hemorrhage. The lens-shaped occurs as extradural hematomas â€œrespect suture linesâ€. As you can see in both of these images, the bleed is restricted to the inner surface of the parietal bone. 
Again, an intracranial bleed can act as a space-occupying lesion and cause a midline shift, as seen here with dotted line C.
